author: Andre Wright
title: Brantley bounces Barbour County
text:
Barbour County stayed close for a half with Brantley, but the Bulldogs scored 27 second-half points in routing the Jaguars, 41-6, Friday night during Homecoming at Brantley Field. 
Barbour County remains winless at 0-8 overall. Brantley, ranked No. 8 in Class 1A, improved to 5-2. 
The Jaguars’ defense recovered a first-quarter fumble caused by J’barius Mathews and Michael Carey knocking the ball free from a Brantley ball carrier. 
However, after Brantley quarterback Jacob Free was sacked by Jaylin Robinson, Free hooked up with Tommy Spivey on a 76-yard catch and run. Nathan Renfroe added the PAT for a 7-0 Bulldogs lead with 53 seconds left in the first quarter. 
Free scored his first touchdown on a 13-yard run in the second quarter, and the Bulldogs led 14-0 at the half. 
Free scored with a 51-yard jaunt right up the middle for a 21-0 lead, then stretched it to 28-0 when he connected with Dee Barginere on a 5-yard pass. 
Jaguars’ quarterback Dywaun Walton hit Marquell Jones on a 27-yard TD pass. Mathews then sprinted 35 yards to the Brantley 4, and Walton eventually scored from a yard out to make it 28-6. 
Brantley added two fourth-quarter scores on a 7-yard run by Xavious Coleman and a 26-yard run by Mark Wise. 
Barbour County finished with 7 first downs; 37 rushes for 77 yards; completed 5-of-20 passes for 102 yards and 3 interceptions; was penalized 7 times for 45 yards. 
Mathews paced Barbour County with 65 yards rushing. Walton passed for 102 yards and had 2 receptions for 63 yards. Robinson had 1 catch for 33 yards. 
Brantley had 12 first downs; rushed for 364 yards; completed 7-of-14 pass for 174 yards and 2 interceptions; had 12 penalties for 101 yards. 
Hunter led the Jaguars’ defense with 13 tackles, had 2 fumble recoveries and a sack. Kavarion Pugh added 9 tackles, Miezan Carey 7 (and a sack), Decourious Rodgers 6, and Michael Carey 5. Deondre McClain and Wilson each had an interception, and Robinson caused a fumble. 
The Jaguars travel to Slocomb Friday.
